{{Citation needed|date=March 29, 2014}}
{{Image request|date=March 29, 2014|cat=Munakata City|image of the festival}}
'''Miare Festival''' (みあれ祭, Miare-sai) is a religious festival held annually on {{ill|October 1|ja|10月1日}} as part of the {{ill|Munakata Taisha|ja|宗像大社}} Autumn Grand Festival (Tajima Hōjō-e) in {{ill|Munakata City|ja|宗像市}}, {{ill|Fukuoka Prefecture|ja|福岡県}}. The festival seeks blessings for maritime safety, successful voyages, and abundant catches.

== Details == 
Munakata Taisha comprises three shrines: '''Hetsu-miya''' on the mainland, '''Nakatsu-miya''' on {{ill|Ōshima|ja|大島 (福岡県)}}, and '''Okitsu-miya''' on {{ill|Okinoshima|ja|沖ノ島}}, each dedicated to one of the {{ill|Three Female Deities of Munakata|ja|宗像三女神}}. During the Miare Festival, {{ill|Ichikishimahime|ja|市杵島姫神}}, enshrined at Hetsu-miya, symbolically welcomes her elder sisters, {{ill|Tagorihime|ja|田心姫神}} and {{ill|Tagitsuhime|ja|湍津姫神}}. 

The event involves a maritime procession where three portable shrines (mikoshi), representing the Munakata Three Goddesses, are placed on ceremonial boats (gozabune). These boats are escorted by a fleet from the Seven Harbors of Munakata (Nanoura) in a large-scale sea parade that includes hundreds of fishing boats. The event highlights the region's ancient seafaring heritage, as the Munakata clan, renowned from prehistoric to ancient times, played a pivotal role in trade and navigation between Japan and the mainland.

[[File:宗像大社みあれ祭.jpg|thumb|Scene from the maritime procession (2014)]]

== Media Appearances ==
The festival was featured in the ending scene of the 2003 NHK Fukuoka regional drama ''Genkai: Watashi no Umi e'' (玄海〜わたしの海へ〜).  
In 2005, it was highlighted in the RKB Mainichi Broadcasting special ''The Story of the Sea and the Goddess: Miare Festival,'' sponsored by {{ill|DyDo Drinco|ja|ダイドードリンコ}}.

== Related Topics ==
* {{ill|Munakata Taisha|ja|宗像大社}}
* {{ill|Boat Procession|ja|船渡御}}
* {{ill|Hōjō-e|ja|放生会}}
* {{ill|Ama People|ja|海人族}}

== References ==
* ''Fukuoka Rekishi Sanpo'' (Historical Stroll through Fukuoka), edited by Fukuoka City (noting Hirano Kuninomi’s involvement in Munakata Taisha renovations).
* {{ill|Shinya Fujiwara|ja|藤原新也}} and {{ill|Ryūtarō Abe|ja|安部龍太郎}}, ''Kami no Shima Okinoshima'' (God’s Island Okinoshima), Shogakukan, 2013.

